Anvil Fall

by: Jason Elliott

This game was made for my level 2 project at The League of Amazing Programmers.
Click here to download and play!

1. Why I Made This Game

When thinking of a game to make, I knew that a fun game includes action, challenges for user, and a purpose to keep playing. Though when thinking of ideas, most of them were complex or could not be done with what I know. And with inspiration from Tetris I was able to design a simple game that is challenging for the player. Anvils would fall at random places along the top of the screen at random speeds, with more falling per second as the game goes on. With the addition of falling clocks that the player has to collect to the the death timer far from zero. If the player runs into an anvil or the timer gets to zero you will die and the game would end.

2. What I Learned

When testing the game ran smoothly, the original version of the game actually did not have a death timer or clocks falling though. It was inspiration from the testers that made me add these features. Overall the final version is much better because it not only stresses one challenge on the user but two. (Falling anvils and timer).

3. Architecture of My Game

Most interactions in the game are related to the user and the falling objects. This includes collision boxes that tell whether the player has hit an anvil and should die or if they have collected a clock to add bonus points to the death timer. And speaking of timers there are multiple set up to interact at different points in the game to make it more difficult as it goes on. For example each falling object has its own timer, and there are several other timers that make certain objects fall more often per second or will start to spawn items at a certain level of the game. Many other interactions that update the collision boxes and timers are used throughout classes to call methods to make the game run as it should.

4. Technical Implementation

The basic goal of the game is to survive as long as possible. With rising difficulty and a death timer that acts almost like a timed bomb puts stress on the user. But I would say if stress is applied correctly, it will make the game entertaining. My goal was to make a game that gave the user more than one task to challenge their skill and not make it frustrating. But at the same time give the user a sense of accomplishment. I would say I am proud that my game is unique from other games out there. Most games have one goal, or one challenge, but this game has two challenges at the same time which forces the user to multitask under pressure. The steps I used to accomplish this goal was testing and opinions from peers. I would use trial and error to fix simple problems or make certain aspects more enjoyable. My game would be much different if I didn't collect ideas from different minds, without ideas from other people, my game would not have many small features that change the whole game.

5. Most Challenging Part

For me, the challenging part of any project big or small is the little things. If one thing is wrong, the whole program fails. And sometimes I would come across a problem that wasn't obvious and I had to look through everything to find the missing link. Though most of the time the program helped me solve the problem, I would need to add/remove/change code to help my game work again.

6. Future Fixes and Updates

If I were to continue to work on this game, I would definitely smooth some edges. What I mean by that is I would make everything, like the title screen, more clear and get a user's attention. I would also would possibly add things for people who want an easier game or an even bigger challenge. But most of all I would take more ideas from people to make the game enjoyable for everyone.
